<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How does wrist circumference determine frame size?", answer: "Wrist circumference is one of the most reliable indicators of skeletal frame size because the wrist has very little fat or muscle, making it a direct measurement of bone structure. For men, a wrist under 16.5 cm indicates a small frame, 16.5-19 cm is medium, and over 19 cm is large. For women, under 14 cm is small, 14-16.5 cm is medium, and over 16.5 cm is large." },
  { question: "Why does frame size matter for ideal weight?", answer: "People with larger skeletal frames naturally weigh more than those with smaller frames at the same height, even at the same body fat percentage. A large-framed person has heavier bones and larger joints, which can account for 10% or more additional body weight. Standard ideal weight formulas that ignore frame size may give misleading targets for people at either end of the frame size spectrum." },
  { question: "How do I measure my wrist circumference?", answer: "Measure your wrist circumference using a flexible tape measure placed just below the wrist bone (ulnar styloid process), where the wrist meets the hand. The tape should be snug but not compressing the skin. Measure your dominant hand. If you do not have a tape measure, wrap a piece of string around your wrist, mark it, and measure the string length with a ruler." },
  { question: "What is the wrist-to-height ratio?", answer: "The wrist-to-height ratio is calculated by dividing wrist circumference by height (both in the same units). This ratio typically ranges from 8% to 12% and provides a normalized measure of frame size that accounts for overall body proportions. A higher ratio indicates a larger frame relative to height." },
  { question: "How are ideal weight ranges calculated?", answer: "This calculator uses the Hamwi method as a base: for men, 48 kg for the first 5 feet plus 2.7 kg per additional inch; for women, 45.5 kg for the first 5 feet plus 2.2 kg per additional inch. The result is then adjusted by plus or minus 10% based on frame size, with a range of plus or minus 10% around the adjusted base to provide a realistic weight range." }
]) %>

